<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,679,1389]" box="[151,1303,679,704]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Black; pronotum with posterior margin edged with orange-brown; forewings with orange-brown spots.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,679,1389]" box="[199,475,716,741]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis box="[199,277,716,741]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Length</emphasis>
Male 
<quantity box="[348,475,716,741]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.4" metricValueMax="3.5" metricValueMin="3.3" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="mm" value="3.4" valueMax="3.5" valueMin="3.3">3.3–3.5mm</quantity>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,679,1389]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis box="[199,375,751,776]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Male genitalia.</emphasis>
Subgenital plate trapezoidal with outer marginal angle obtuse and conically rounded apex. Style with preapical lobe well developed, apical apophysis short, fingerlike, slightly curved laterally. Connective short dorsal apodeme, shaft curved dorsally and then anteriorly narrowed towards apex, with large gonopore on ventral margin. somewhat Y-shaped, with platelike stem about as long as wide, arms short. Aedeagus with well developed but
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,594,932,957]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,679,1389]" box="[199,594,932,957]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,432,932,957]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Material examined.</emphasis>
See Remarks.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,679,1389]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,967,992]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Remarks</emphasis>
. This species was described from an unknown number of specimens from 
<collectingCountry box="[1167,1279,967,992]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<collectingRegion box="[1167,1200,967,992]" country="United Kingdom" name="Surrey" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Sri</collectingRegion>
Lanka
</collectingCountry>
with the data “Des Montagnes Nura-Ellia et Patannas”. In 
<collectionCode box="[663,741,1004,1028]" country="Russia" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/m34f-agji" name="Zoological Museum, Saratov State University" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">ZMSU</collectionCode>
among the Motschulsky collection from 
<collectingCountry box="[1211,1325,1004,1029]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<collectingRegion box="[1211,1244,1004,1029]" country="United Kingdom" name="Surrey" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Sri</collectingRegion>
Lanka
</collectingCountry>
, there are two male specimens (now cleaned and photographed, 
<figureCitation box="[754,910,1039,1064]" captionStart="FIGURES192–202" captionStartId="38.[151,264,1901,1924]" captionTargetBox="[172,1410,221,1845]" captionTargetId="figure@38.[151,1436,193,1881]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES192–202. Motschulsky’s species of Penthimia. 192–200.P.rufopunctata. 192.Valve, ventral view; 193. Subgenital plate, ventral view; 194. Style, dorsal view; 195. Connective, dorsal view; 196. Aedeagus, lateral view; 197. Aedeagus, posterodorsal view; 198. Label data on the type; 199. Type male dorsal view; 200. Topotype male, dorsal view. 201–202. P. melanocephala. 201, Female dorsal view; 202. Female ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1135516/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Figs 199–200</figureCitation>
, by Dmitri Tishechkin, pers. comm.) that agree with the original description of 
<taxonomicName box="[506,679,1076,1100]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Penthimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufopunctata">
<emphasis box="[506,679,1076,1100]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">P. rufopunctata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but with barely discernable labels. One male (
<figureCitation box="[1202,1298,1076,1101]" captionStart="FIGURES192–202" captionStartId="38.[151,264,1901,1924]" captionTargetBox="[172,1410,221,1845]" captionTargetId="figure@38.[151,1436,193,1881]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES192–202. Motschulsky’s species of Penthimia. 192–200.P.rufopunctata. 192.Valve, ventral view; 193. Subgenital plate, ventral view; 194. Style, dorsal view; 195. Connective, dorsal view; 196. Aedeagus, lateral view; 197. Aedeagus, posterodorsal view; 198. Label data on the type; 199. Type male dorsal view; 200. Topotype male, dorsal view. 201–202. P. melanocephala. 201, Female dorsal view; 202. Female ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1135516/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 199</figureCitation>
) bears a red rectangular label with yellow circle bearing ‘type’ which is hardly possible to make out (
<figureCitation box="[1172,1269,1111,1136]" captionStart="FIGURES192–202" captionStartId="38.[151,264,1901,1924]" captionTargetBox="[172,1410,221,1845]" captionTargetId="figure@38.[151,1436,193,1881]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES192–202. Motschulsky’s species of Penthimia. 192–200.P.rufopunctata. 192.Valve, ventral view; 193. Subgenital plate, ventral view; 194. Style, dorsal view; 195. Connective, dorsal view; 196. Aedeagus, lateral view; 197. Aedeagus, posterodorsal view; 198. Label data on the type; 199. Type male dorsal view; 200. Topotype male, dorsal view. 201–202. P. melanocephala. 201, Female dorsal view; 202. Female ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1135516/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 198</figureCitation>
) and the other with similar label but without the inscription ‘type’ belonging to the same species (Dmitri Ticheshkin, pers. comm.). Dr. Tishechkin informs that “The color of spots on forewings is difficult to distinguish against black abdomen.....the spots on the hind margin are semitransparent greyish, and more proximal spots are reddish brown”. The specimen with 
<typeStatus box="[374,422,1256,1280]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">type</typeStatus>
label has been dissected and the male genitalia photographed (
<figureCitation box="[1139,1300,1255,1280]" captionStart="FIGURES192–202" captionStartId="38.[151,264,1901,1924]" captionTargetBox="[172,1410,221,1845]" captionTargetId="figure@38.[151,1436,193,1881]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES192–202. Motschulsky’s species of Penthimia. 192–200.P.rufopunctata. 192.Valve, ventral view; 193. Subgenital plate, ventral view; 194. Style, dorsal view; 195. Connective, dorsal view; 196. Aedeagus, lateral view; 197. Aedeagus, posterodorsal view; 198. Label data on the type; 199. Type male dorsal view; 200. Topotype male, dorsal view. 201–202. P. melanocephala. 201, Female dorsal view; 202. Female ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1135516/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Figs 192–197</figureCitation>
). Externally and in the male genitalia this species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shobharani &amp; Viraktamath &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2018" box="[706,880,1293,1316]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Penthimia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="neoattenuata">
<emphasis box="[706,880,1293,1316]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">P. neoattenuata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but the aedeagus has a much larger gonopore and thinner aedeagal shaft in lateral view. The specimen from 
<collectingCountry box="[823,934,1327,1352]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<collectingRegion box="[823,856,1327,1352]" country="United Kingdom" name="Surrey" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Sri</collectingRegion>
Lanka
</collectingCountry>
identified by 
<bibRefCitation author="Distant" box="[1098,1263,1327,1352]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" refString="Distant, W. L. (1908) Rhynchota: Homoptera and Appendix (Pt). In: Bingham, C. T. (Ed.), The Fauna of British India including Ceylon and Burma. Vol. 4. Taylor &amp; Francis, London, pp. 1 - 501." type="book" year="1908">Distant (1908)</bibRefCitation>
as this species (
<collectionCode box="[158,245,1364,1388]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">BMNH</collectionCode>
) belongs to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Melichar" authorityYear="1903" box="[383,499,1364,1389]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Neodartus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[383,499,1364,1389]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Neodartus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
